# Sacrotuberous Ligament

> The **sacrotuberous ligament** is a strong broad ligament connecting the sacrum/coccyx to the [[Ischial Tuberosity]], converting the greater sciatic notch into the greater sciatic foramen and the lesser sciatic notch into the lesser sciatic foramen.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — Sacrum + coccyx (lateral border) + PSIS
- **Insertion** — [[Ischial Tuberosity]]
- **Related structures** — Greater sciatic foramen (above), lesser sciatic foramen (below)
- **Biceps Femoris** — Long head has a fibrous expansion into the sacrotuberous ligament

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Pelvic stability** — Resists nutation of the sacrum (forward tilting)
- **SIJ dysfunction** — Sacrotuberous ligament tension influences sacroiliac joint mechanics
- **Pudendal nerve** — Pudendal nerve (S2–S4) exits greater sciatic foramen and re-enters through lesser sciatic foramen, close to sacrotuberous ligament

## 📍 Location
[[Skeletal System]] → Lower Limb → Sacrotuberous Ligament (Pelvis)

